The paper deals with graph partitioning algorithms and their analysis, which falls under the category of theoretical computer science. The use of eigenvalues and Laplacian systems suggests that the paper may belong to the sub-category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The focus on graph expansion and spectral partitioning also suggests the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI), computational geometry (cs.CG), and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the mention of personal pagerank vectors and truncated random walk algorithm suggests the sub-category of information theory (cs.IT).
